DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain examines theories of moral responsibility, control, and agency,
particularly as they relate to delegation and collaborative action. The literature
divides into several key debates: (1) The control condition debate, centered on
Fischer and Ravizza's guidance control versus regulative control requiring alternative
possibilities; (2) The reactive attitudes tradition following Strawson's seminal
paper, examining when blame and praise are appropriate; (3) Complicity and shared
responsibility, investigating how individuals bear responsibility for collective
outcomes; and (4) Recent applications to AI and technology, exploring responsibility
gaps when autonomous systems mediate action. Christopher Kutz's work on complicity
without causal contribution is particularly relevant to delegation, as is Bratman's
account of shared agency through interlocking intentions.

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The moral value of doing things yourself depends critically on whether delegating
tasks diminishes responsibility or merely distributes it. Fischer and Ravizza's
guidance control framework suggests responsibility tracks one's reasons-responsive
mechanism, not direct causal contribution. Kutz's complicity principle argues
participants share responsibility even when individual contributions are causally
inert. These debates directly address whether delegation compromises moral standing.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While extensive literature exists on collective responsibility and shared agency,
few papers directly examine the ethical significance of *choosing* to delegate
versus performing tasks oneself. The intrinsic value (not just instrumental
efficiency) of personal action remains under-explored. Recent AI ethics work
addresses responsibility gaps but focuses on accountability rather than the
moral significance of retaining agency. Jensen and Mellema are both missing abstracts.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Distinguish between: (1) causal responsibility (making a difference), (2) moral
responsibility (eligibility for praise/blame), and (3) what we might call
"authorship" (the value of an outcome tracking to one's own agency). The DIY
project may concern the third category more than the first two.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Control-based theories: 6 papers - Responsibility requires appropriate control (guidance vs. regulative)
- Complicity theories: 4 papers - Participation generates responsibility independent of causal contribution
- Shared agency theories: 4 papers - Joint action through interlocking intentions and plural subjects
- Applied AI ethics: 4 papers - Responsibility gaps and distributed responsibility in technological systems
