  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Kutz argues for a "Complicity Principle" under which individuals are accountable for harms they participate in, even when their individual contribution makes no difference to the outcome. He rejects the "difference principle" that ties responsibility to causal efficacy, proposing instead that participation in collective endeavors generates responsibility based on shared intentionality, not individual causal contribution.

  RELEVANCE: Central to the delegation question. If Kutz is right that participation matters more than causal difference-making, then delegating tasks to others may not absolve one of responsibility—one remains complicit in the outcome. However, this raises the reverse question: does retaining tasks rather than delegating also constitute a morally significant choice about participation?

  POSITION: Participation-based responsibility; challenges individualism about moral responsibility.
  },
  keywords = {complicity, shared-responsibility, participation, High},
  abstract = {We live in a morally flawed world. Our lives are complicated by what other people do, and by the harms that flow from our social, economic and political institutions. Our relations as individuals to these collective harms constitute the domain of complicity. This book examines the relationship between collective responsibility and individual guilt. It presents a rigorous philosophical account of the nature of our relations to the social groups in which we participate, and uses that account in a discussion of contemporary moral theory. Christopher Kutz shows that the two prevailing theories of moral philosophy, Kantianism and consequentialism, both have difficulties resolving problems of complicity. He then argues for a richer theory of accountability in which any real understanding of collective action not only allows but demands individual responsibility.},
  abstract_source = {openalex},
}

